Impact of covid-19 in mobility

Overview

Abstract

COVID-19 is a pandemic disease that has wreaked havoc in all countries all over the world, from China to nearly every country. It had an influence on human life, the global economy, and the Wearable technology market. The pandemic scenario has had a significant influence on mobility behavior. Depending on data provided from apple and using R to analyze these data to see the mobility behavior of the people and how can we use the results to make the right decision to develop a program or provide a sensor with a specific feature to a wearable product.

Keywords

Covid-19, mobility, R graphics, ggplot.

1.Introduction

COVID-19 was first discovered in Wuhan city in China in December 2019. The rapid growth in the number of cases outside of China prompted the WHO Director-General to declare the outbreak a pandemic on March 11, 2020. More than 118 000 cases have been reported in 114 countries by that time, with 4291 mortalities [1].

The Covid-19 pandemic changed the face of the world affecting, on the one hand, the global economy, and in the other hand the behavior of the people particularly in terms of mobility and social distance.

Luckily, organizations across the world have been gathering data so that we can keep track of the pandemic and learn from it to make the right decisions depending on the data we will use and the purpose of the analysis. Apple’s mobility trend reports, which are dependent on location information via Apple’s “maps” services, illustrate how human mobility has altered in countries and cities around the world since January 2020 we can download this data from apple ‘s website [2]. There are many tools to analyze and visualize data, in this analysis R and RStudio will be used which is an open-source and publicly available software environment for data processing, computing, analysis, and graphical display [3].

2.Problem definition

State of the art

Some researchers investigate visualizations based on Google data [4], [5]. The visualizations was created for varying reasons to the COVID-19 pandemic. Other research investigates the role of human mobility studies in dealing with COVID-19 [6], [7],[8].

Aim of the work

In this analysis, we want to explore data gained from maps of apple to we will visualize and how can we interpret the results to make the right decision to meet our goal to find the best potential market and to explore the options for the client company to know which potential markets are the most interesting for the new line of products of the sports market and to decide whether to create a new service of the wearable product or improve existing ones.

3.Objective

Dataset: The data used is COVID-19 Community Mobility Report from January 2020 to July 2020 to see mobility trends during the COVID-19 pandemic. The data is in the form of a CSV file that contains mobility data for directions requests per country, region, or city in comparison to a baseline volume on January 13th, 2020[2]. In this analysis we will focus on Brazil, Germany, and United States using R programming language and RStudio.

4.Methods

R programming language and RStudio are used to process data. The main libraries used mainly are ‘readr’ to import data as Tibble “the nice form of the data frame which make it easier in handling” instead of using R’s default data frame, ‘dplyr’ for data wrangling and manipulation, and ‘ggplot’ for data visualization which based on the grammar of graphic Importing the csv file in the form of Tibble using ‘readr’ library.

  • Data wrangling: reconstructing the data in the proper form and dealing with the missing values.
  • Variable constraints: set the variables (columns) to the proper data type.
  • Statical methods: use statical analysis and summary statistics such as box plot and summary function.
  • Visualization: using of ggplot library to draw graphs and performing time series analysis.

5. Results and discussion

Impact of covid in mobility

Mobility between various places is impacted differently by regions and economic levels. For the most part, Latin America has the biggest effect. High-income countries have the most significant variations from the baseline among income levels[9].

Based on these facts, United States has been chosen as one of the biggest markets in the world to invest in. And from Europe, the biggest economic country in Europe which is Germany has been selected. Also, we must take into consideration the Southern hemisphere. Because, the seasons of the year differ in the southern and northern hemispheres, and this can affect in some way the Covid situation and affect the behavior of mobility at the same time of the year. Brazil is one of the best-developing countries to choose with the biggest Population in South America. So, the analysis was done in these 3 countries to see if these Potential Markets are the right to target.

When comparing driving, public transportation, and walking across all regions, a reduction of 60 to nearly 80% can be found when compared to the baseline of 13 January 2020. The decrease began on March 8, 2020, and the lowest point was in early April. Public transportation has experienced the greatest fall, with a 76 % at its lowest point in April 2020 We can see this also in the article provided by Slocat partnership [9].

Fig1 : A graph from the analysis shows a time series analysis for the 3 countries.

We can observe from this graph that there is a transition from using public transportation to using private cars. what supports this result a research done by Juliane Anke, Angela Francke, Lisa-Marie Schaefer & Tibor Petzoldt impact in covid-19 in mobility behavior in Germany where Data showed a significant impact on mobility behavior, with a move away from public transportation and an increase in private vehicles[10].

Fig2 : Modal split differences (during-before COVID-19) for the lockdown and no lockdown group.

From: Impact of SARS-CoV-2 on the mobility behaviour in Germany Fig3[10].

When comparing the two groups in Fig2, the lockdown group has a bigger jump in walking and lower utilization of public transportation, we can see this also in Fig1 especially in Brazil and the United States. There was a higher rise in car use without lockdown than with lockdown.

Impact of COVID-19 on consumer behavior

The COVID-19 situation is influencing customer behavior and, as a result, marketing strategies. Consumers are being pushed to reconsider their objectives in life. Several trends have been recognized by Euromonitor International, including: Healthy life: It is becoming increasingly necessary to have a healthy lifestyle and practice healthy behaviors both inside and outside the home. Purchasing Reimagined: Many consumers are shifting to internet shopping as a result of social distancing[11].

6. Conclusion

From the analysis, we can see that Covid-19 has a great effect in mobility behavior a drop in map requests in Germany, Brazil, and the United States happened during the lockdown. Consequently, as a customer with the lack of movement and the closure of sports clubs, the priority will be health concerns, especially as it will improve the immune system to face any possible infection from the virus. An article supports this hypothesis which mentioned that the sudden emergence of the COVID-19 pandemic has had a beneficial effect on the worldwide sports gear industry’s growth. Due to the closure of gyms and fitness facilities during the lockdown, demand for home fitness equipment has surged. In addition, the outbreak has raised public awareness about the importance of maintaining personal health [11].

According to that, the Company can work in developing sensors in the wearable product to measure the heart rate or count the number of calories burned and we can pass an idea to the research and development department to see if it is possible to make a sensor which can measure the oxygen level in the blood which is helpful in diagnosing Covid-19 and monitoring Covid-19 mild cases at home[12]. If they succeed in that, the company will sell a lot.

we can also develop a program to tell the customers about the risky areas near them that which will raise an alarm and then no need to smartphones when the customers go jogging or running as some people prefer to leave their smartphones at home when they are doing some outdoor sports, and the product will be the magic solutions for this with its multifunctionality properties.

Thus, the product will be effective whether the person stays at home or doing outdoors or indoors sport, we can target all kind of customers. some will buy it for the reason to go outside counting their steps burning some calories. While the others will buy it because they may concern about checking the heart rate and blood pressure.

Data Wrangling and cleaning

One crucial rule to follow while cleaning up our dataset is to put each variable (the date) inthe same column.

mobility <- df %>%  gather(date, req_num ,"2020-01-13":"2020-06-30")
#with Pipe operator I pass the data to the gather function and make two coloumns which are the Date and the map requests count

Dealing with the missing values

Depending on our purpose of the analysis, we will deal with missing values, which are represented here by NA (not available). For example, we can take the mean of the variable and fill in the missing values with the result. However, we will work in specific regions. So, we don’t have to do that, instead, we will remove these values.

Check for the missing values in the “map requests count” column

sum(is.na(mobility$req_num)) #is.na to check for missing values and with sum func we weill know the count
## [1] 13802

Bringing all the three countries together for better comparison

We can use ggplot to see the behavior of different means of transport on the same graph. In the geom_bar() I will use the position parameter and assign dodge to it which allows us to make bar plots side by side to easily compare their variables.

In the geom_bar() I will use the position parameter and assign dodge to it which allows us to make bar plots side by side to easily compare their variables.

It is better to choose the theme minimal for better Visualisation not to distract our Audience, or obscure the graph with a lot of unnecessary data.

to improve the graph’s communication, it is good to choose a title of the graph which represents what the graph is telling us, or talking about, instead of just putting the x-axis vs y-axis. Also, scales have to be taken into consideration.

ggplot(target_market,  aes(region, req_num ))+
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", aes(fill=transportation_type), position = "dodge")+ #use fill arg in aestestics enables us to choose the filled color depend on the region
  labs(title ="Germany shows the use of Public transport more than US and Brazil",
       subtitle="Brazil Uses Private cars the least ", y = "Count of map reuests", x ="")+
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 210, 20))+
  coord_flip()+
  theme_minimal()

we will see later the change of that over time

Quantitative univariate analysis

Analysis of a single numeric variable (Map requests Count)

the measure of the location of the data(central tendency), the spread of the data, shape.

Create a box plot of the number of requests of the maps

with a boxplot, we can see 5-number summary statistics for a single quantitative variable (number of map requests).

ggplot(target_market, aes(x=req_num)) +
  geom_boxplot(fill="sky blue")+
  labs(title = "Distribution of the map requests count")+
  theme_minimal()

from the box plot we can see that, the min is around 15 and the max is around 171, Median is 84

Comparison of the distribution of numeric value in the three regions

we can use fill parameter in aes() to visualize the difference of the distribution of the map requests between the three regions. for better visualizing, we will add the layer coordinate and view the box plot vertically.

ggplot(target_market, aes(x=req_num)) +
  geom_boxplot(notch = T, aes(fill=region),alpha=.8)+
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set2") + # choose another color palette
  labs(title = "Distribution of the Map request count in the 3 Countries")+
  coord_flip()+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 210, 20))+
  theme_minimal()

Time series Analysis

a common and better way to figure the change over time is the line graph. I have chosen the colors for the three countries manually to express the most dominant color that represents their flags.

Mobility trends in Germany

In Germany, the map requests started to decrease in March and reached their lowest level in April during the lockdown to combat the spread of infection.

Walking vs Public Transport

  labs(x = "Date",
    y = "Map requests count",
    title = "Mobility trends in Germany for Walking and Public Transport ")+
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 200, 20))+
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE) +
  facet_grid(. ~ transportation_type)+
  theme_minimal()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Slightly different when it compared with driving, which might because because lately some people are taking the precautions less seriously like the beginnig.
